Rating: 2
Don't make this without the acorn squash. The soup itself is OK but since it's meant to be pureed it needs the squash for texture. My fiance said the squash was the best part of this and I have to agree with him. Because everything's going to be pureed in the end anyhow, save yourself the trouble of chopping things and throw everything in the food processor ahead of time (separately of course since the ingredients aren't all added at the same time). Not only does that cut down on prep time, everything's in tiny pieces which cooks through faster. Also, I started with half the recommended amount of liquids (broth and water). You can add more at the end after everything's pureed and just blend it together over the heat. This will keep the soup to whatever your desired thickness is. Season generously. I also threw in a store-bought dry herb mix I had and I think that really helped add some more depth to the soup (basil, oregano, mint, sage, rosemary...), cayenne added a nice kick as well. I didn't use the full two tablespoons of vinegar, I think it would've overwhelmed the beet flavor. This is a soup you really need to taste as you go, don't just measure out the ingredients ahead of time and throw it all in. I also threw in a small carrot into the mix of ingredients just to add some more flavor (I didn't really taste it at all though). I really wouldn't say this soup is anything special. The whole thing is incredibly filling though. While I don't think I'd make this soup again I think by halving the liquids this would make a delicious pasta sauce.

