Rating: 3
I made this for my fiancee who loves beets and squash. He loved it but I think I could make it better next time with a few changes in technique and a few ingredient changes. Changes when I made this dish - I didn't cut a slice off the bottom of the squash. I chose one that was already pretty flat and as it cooked, it settled down and became even flatter and more stable. I figured that the skin of the squash would help it remain whole while it cooked if I didn't cut it and I could help stabilize the bottom of the bowl if it was still unstable by putting greens like lettuce under the squash if it was still too unstable. I discovered that I'd forgotten to buy an apple and my chicken stock had expired. I substituted a pear for the apple and I used beef broth with some apple cider in it. I also only pureed half of the mixture and mixed the two halfs together and found I enjoyed the texture, although the beet bits were a bit tough. Changes for next time:use vegetable broth. I'm going to sautee the onions, then the beets, then the garlic and cook the beets in the stock/water mixture for 30 minutes on med/high. Puree the beet mixture, then add cubed apples and pears to cook for 15 minutes longer on med. Also, the part of the squash lid touching the sheet burned, turned black, and tasted bitter. Next time I'm going to put a little water in a cake pan and put the lid into it, then put the cake pan on the cookie sheet with the bowl of the squash and cook them together. Also, an hour and 15 minutes was too long to cook the squash. I'm going to check the squash at 45 minutes next time to make sure it doesn't overcook, then every 10 minutes.

